n activation to plasmin","Inhibits thrombin formation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETranexamic acid (TXA) works by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting plasminogen activation to plasmin\u003C/strong\u003E. It is a synthetic lysine analogue that competitively binds to plasminogen, preventing its conversion to plasmin. This reduces fibrinolysis and helps maintain formed blood clots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other, incorrect options are explained below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates platelet aggregation\u003C/strong\u003E: TXA does not directly affect platelet function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivates the coagulation cascade\u003C/strong\u003E: TXA does not initiate or enhance coagulation directly. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases fibrinogen synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E: TXA does not affect the production of coagulation factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits thrombin formation\u003C/strong\u003E: TXA works on the fibrinolytic system, not the coagulation cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing fibrin breakdown, tranexamic acid is effective in reducing blood loss in various clinical scenarios including trauma, surgery, and heavy menstrual bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tranexamic acid is an antifibrinolytic agent that competitively inhibits plasminogen activation to plasmin.","By preventing fibrin breakdown, tranexamic acid helps maintain blood clots and reduce bleeding.","Tranexamic acid is commonly used to treat or prevent excessive bleeding in trauma, surgery, and heavy menstrual bleeding."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","